quran[9]{c,v,t,f}:
  2,121,"Those to whom We have given the Book recite it with its true recital.{1} They [are the ones who] believe in it. And whoever disbelieves in it - it is they who are the losers.",footnotes:1:[i.e., applying its teachings to their lives.]
  2,122,"O Children of Israel, remember My favor which I have bestowed upon you and that I preferred you over the worlds."
  2,123,"And fear a Day when no soul will suffice for another soul{1} at all, and no compensation will be accepted from it, nor will any intercession benefit it, nor will they be aided.",footnotes:1:[See footnote to 2:48.]
  3,61,"Then whoever argues with you about it after [this] knowledge has come to you - say, "
  3,62,"Indeed, this is the true narration. And there is no deity except Allāh. And indeed, Allāh is the Exalted in Might, the Wise."
  3,63,"But if they turn away, then indeed - Allāh is Knowing of the corrupters."
  4,1,"O mankind, fear your Lord, who created you from one soul and created from it its mate and dispersed from both of them many men and women. And fear Allāh, through whom{1} you ask one another,{2} and the wombs.{3} Indeed Allāh is ever,{4} over you, an Observer.{5}",footnotes:1:[In whose name.],footnotes:2:[i.e., request favors and demand rights.],footnotes:3:[i.e., fear Allāh in regard to relations of kinship.],footnotes:4:[When used in conjunction with Allāh's attributes, the word \"ever\" (occurring repeatedly throughout this sūrah and elsewhere, such as in Sūrah al-Aḥzāb) is quite inadequate in imparting the sense of continuation expressed by the word \"kāna\" in Arabic, which indicates \"always was, is, and always will be.\"],footnotes:5:[Ever-present and taking account of everything.]
  4,2,"And give to the orphans their properties and do not substitute the defective [of your own] for the good [of theirs]. And do not consume their properties into your own. Indeed, that is ever a great sin."
  4,3,"And if you fear that you will not deal justly with the orphan girls, then marry those that please you of [other] women, two or three or four. But if you fear that you will not be just, then [marry only] one or those your right hands possess [i.e., slaves]. That is more suitable that you may not incline [to injustice]."
